{{location map marker |England |lat=51.398289 |long=-0.085536 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;top:6px;">[[Selhurst Park]]</div>|position=right}}
{{location map end |England |caption=The locations of the three stadia used by [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] during the scope of this article, [[Plough Lane]], [[Selhurst Park]] and the [[National Hockey Stadium]] in [[Milton Keynes]], are given here.}}
<!-- Advice to editors: Wikipedia is not a fan site.  The article must remain factual and maintain a neutral point of view -->
[[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon Football Club]] was an English professional [[Association football|football]] club from [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]], south-west [[London]]. Founded in 1889, the club spent most of its history in amateur and semi-professional [[non-League football]] prior to a "fairytale" rise through the divisions following election to [[The Football League]] in 1977. This success resulted in the club looking to move from its home ground, [[Plough Lane]], and seeking an alternative base.

Relocation to [[Milton Keynes]], a [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new town]] {{convert|56|mi|km|0}} to the north of Wimbledon, was originally considered in the late 1970s, soon after the club's election to the Football League, but not followed up. Various abortive local options were explored during the 1980s, but the 1991 [[Taylor Report]], which recommended all-seater stadia for all top-flight clubs, led the team to temporarily [[groundshare]] with [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] at [[Selhurst Park]] whilst an alternative was sought. 

Milton Keynes, because of its foundation and designation as a new town in 1967, represented a unique situation in English football in that there was no professional team representing it that had secured the loyalty of local supporters. Wimbledon were not the only team to be approached regarding a move there &ndash; a move by Charlton was briefly mooted in 1973 and the subject was regularly broached with [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], most notably in 1982. In the early 2000s, the Milton Keynes Stadium Consortium, led by [[Pete Winkelman]], proposed a Football League-standard stadium in Milton Keynes, partly funded by an attached retail development. The opportunity to take up this new ground was offered to Luton, Wimbledon, [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]], Crystal Palace and [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]. Despite an initial negative response from Wimbledon, the appointment in 2000 by its owners of a new chairman, Charles Koppel, led to more receptive talks. 

The Wimbledon board announced its intention to move the club to Milton Keynes in August 2001; received permission in May 2002; and did so in September 2003. Soon after the relocation's confirmation in May 2002, supporters opposed to the move formed a new team, [[AFC Wimbledon]].  The relocated club renamed itself [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] in June 2004 and after a period of time playing at the [[National Hockey Stadium]], moved to a new 22,000 seat stadium in the town playing their first game at the new ground in July 2007.

==Background to the relocation==
===The new town of Milton Keynes===
{{main|Milton Keynes}}
Following the end of the [[World War II|Second World War]] in 1945, the population of [[London]] increased significantly, causing the construction of a number of [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new towns]] across the south-east of England. [[London overspill|Overspill]] housing for several London boroughs was constructed in [[Bletchley]], in north [[Buckinghamshire]], by [[London County Council]].<ref>{{cite web 
 | publisher = Clutch Club
 | location = Milton Keynes
 | url = http://clutch.open.ac.uk/schools/eaton-overspill00/begining.html 
 | accessdate = 2007-01-03 
 | title= Bletchley: Early Days of Overspill: Beginning}}</ref><ref>{{cite web 
 | publisher = Clutch Club
 | location = Milton Keynes
 | url = http://clutch.open.ac.uk/schools/eaton-overspill00/housing.html 
 | accessdate = 2007-01-03 
 | title= Bletchley: Early Days of Overspill: Housing}}</ref><ref name="nfmptitse">{{cite journal
 | date = 1964-12-02
 | title = Need for more planned towns in the South-East
 | journal = [[The Times]]
 | location = London
 | publisher = Times Newspapers
 }}</ref> With this not proving to be enough, a Ministry of Housing and Local Government (MoH&LG) study proposed "a new city" near Bletchley in 1964.<ref>"South East Study 1961&ndash;1981 HMSO 1964", Llewelyn-Davies (1970).</ref> Bletchley, which had been considered for designation in its own right, became instead only a part of the planned development: A further MoH&LG study in 1965 recommended that the existing towns of [[Stony Stratford]] and [[Wolverton]] should also be included.<ref>"Northampton, Bedford and North Bucks", Llewelyn-Davies (1970).</ref><ref name="uatmLhn">{{cite journal
 | date = 1965-02-04
 | title = Urgent action to meet London housing needs
 | journal = [[The Times]]
 | location = London
 | publisher = Times Newspapers
 }}</ref> A target population of 250,000 was given for what was to be the biggest new town of all, built on an area previously home to about 40,000.<ref name="taotNTib6a">{{cite journal
 | date = 1966-01-14
 | title = The area of the New Town increased by 6,000&nbsp;acres (24 km<U+00B2>)
 | journal = [[The Times]]
 | location = London
 | publisher = Times Newspapers
 }}</ref> "[[Milton Keynes]]", named after the [[Middleton, Milton Keynes|village of Milton Keynes]] already present on the site and purposely placed equidistant from London, [[Birmingham]], [[Leicester]], [[Oxford]] and [[Cambridge]],<ref name="Llewelyn-Davies">Llewelyn-Davies (1968).</ref>  was [[History of Milton Keynes#1960s Plans for a new city in North Buckinghamshire, 1967 designation of Milton Keynes|designated]] as a new town on 23 January 1967.<ref name="Designation">{{cite journal
 | date = 1967-24-01
 | page = 827
 | title = The "North Buckinghamshire (Milton Keynes) New Town (Designation) Order"
 | journal = [[London Gazette]]
 | location = London
 | publisher = Her Majesty's Stationery Office
 }}</ref><ref name="Ntwbhf2LPfBa">{{cite journal
 | date = 1967-13-01
 | title = New town will be home for 250,000 Londoners : Plan for Buckinghamshire approved
 | journal = [[The Times]]
 | location = London
 | publisher = Times Newspapers
 }}</ref>

All of the football clubs present within the boundaries of the new town were playing outside [[The Football League]]. The largest of these teams were [[United Counties League]] sides [[Milton Keynes City F.C.|Bletchley Town]] and [[Wolverton A.F.C.|Wolverton Town & B.R.]],{{ref label|MKCity|A|a}}{{ref label|Wolverton|B|}}<ref name="ucleaguetables">{{cite web 
