===Previous Milton Keynes relocation proposals===

{{main|Relocation of professional sports teams#United Kingdom}}
In English football, the relocation of teams away from their traditional districts is extremely unusual because of nature of the relationship between clubs and their local fans: the local football club is regarded by most English football supporters as part of the local identity and social fabric rather than as a business that can be transplanted by its owners at will. As a result, any relocation plan would be strongly opposed by fans in the club's original area, and unlikely to succeed in most new locations due to the existence of established local clubs in most towns and cities that would already have secured the loyalty of local supporters. However, due to its recent establishment in 1967, Milton Keynes provided an exception to this rule; most people living there had been born and raised elsewhere,<ref name="mkweb1">{{cite web
| title = History in Milton Keynes
| url = http://www.mkweb.co.uk/Milton_Keynes_General/DisplayArticle.asp?ID=285
| work = MK Web
| location = Cambridge
| publisher = Iliffe News and Media Limited
| accessdate = 2010-05-09}}</ref> and no team representing Milton Keynes or any of its constituent towns had yet risen high enough in the [[English football league system|football pyramid]] to secure their loyalty.<ref name=mkc/>

====Charlton Athletic====

[[File:South Stand2.jpg|thumb|right|[[The Valley (London)|The Valley]]'s [[Jimmy Seed]] Stand, pictured in 2008, was built during the early 1980s.]]
The first Football League team to be linked with a move to the new town was [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]], in 1973. The club was in financial difficulties and had just been relegated to the third tier at the end of the [[1971<U+2013>72 in English football|1971&ndash;72]] campaign.<ref name=CAFC1973programme/><ref name="fchdcafc">{{cite web
|url=http://www.fchd.btinternet.co.uk/CHARLTOA.HTM
|title=Football Club History Database - Charlton Athletic
|first=Richard
|last=Rundle
|publisher=Football Club History Database
|accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref> Towards the end of the [[1972<U+2013>73 in English football|1972&ndash;73]] season, Charlton revealed plans for commercial extensions to their ground, [[The Valley (London)|The Valley]]: a community sports complex and a public market to be held on weekdays.<ref name=CAFC1973programme/> [[London Borough of Greenwich|Greenwich Council]] refused to licence the market and insisted that the complex be built on public space at a local park,<ref name=CAFC1973programme/> leading the club to announce that it could potentially relocate and that there was "an approach from a progressive Midlands borough".<ref name=CAFC1973programme/><ref name="KentishIndepedendent">{{cite journal
 | date = 1973-04
 | location = London
 | journal = ''The Kentish Independent''
 }}</ref> The club then stated that it was "in no way disenchanted with the district or with the fans" and that there was "no possibility" of the club leaving the ground unless it was "forced out by the attitude of Greenwich Council".<ref name=CAFC1973programme/> Charlton encouraged supporters to "[protest] as loud as you can to Greenwich Council" in order to "make sure the club continues in Charlton".<ref name=CAFC1973programme/> Fans "flooded the club and the local papers" with opinion against any move, and although the club was indeed approached by Milton Keynes authorities, no relocation occurred.<ref name="CAFC1973programme">{{cite journal
 | date = 1973-04-14
 | title = Programme Notes
 | publisher = [[Charlton Athletic F.C.]]
 | journal = Charlton Athletic match programme
 | quote = There is no possibility of Charlton Athletic leaving The Valley unless we are forced out by the attitude of Greenwich Council. We wish to make this clear to our supporters who have flooded the club and the local papers this week, with letters following the announcement that we could move. The roots of Charlton Athletic Football Club are in this area and we are in no way disenchanted with the district or with the fans.
We are frustrated and disappointed by the attitude of Greenwich Council, who have stopped our plans to utilise The Valley during weekdays for the general benefit of the community and like other professional football clubs, we have got to look to the future for ways of safeguarding the club in the 1980s. One sure way is to make much more use of the facilities we have at our disposal.
We believe our plans for a sports complex and a 200-stall open market would have helped both the club and the Charlton area, much of which is in a depressed state and would have been the first step in creating a new concept in community participation.
You the supporters, can make sure the club continues in Charlton by protesting as loud as you can to Greenwich Council over their refusal to grant us permission for our plans. On Wednesday, the council met and discussed a scheme to site the sports complex in nearby Charlton Park on public open space. We still think this decision should be changed and feel sure that eventually common sense will prevail and lead to cooperation between the club and the council concerning the market.
As an interim pleasure we can under existing legislation operate the market for a limited number of days a year and intend to do this and by so doing prove the point of the value to the community.}}</ref>

[[File:PloughLane.jpg|thumb|left|[[Plough Lane]]'s South Stand, pictured in 2000]]
====Wimbledon====
Because of Wimbledon's "fairytale"<ref name="toobigfortheirroots">{{cite news
| title = Too big for their roots
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/1470328.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| first = Stuart
| last = Roach
| date = 2001-08-02
| accessdate = 2009-08-31}}</ref> rise from obscurity through [[English football league system|the English football pyramid]], the team quickly "outgrew"<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> their [[Plough Lane]] ground after their election to [[The Football League]] in 1977.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> [[Ron Noades]], club chairman at the time, claimed in 2003 to have "[seen] the limitations in Plough Lane" as early as 1979, and to have also cited the side's location as the reason for the club's continuing low gates at that time.<ref name=noadesradio/>

Noades's interest was attracted by the site designated by the local Milton Keynes authority for a stadium next to the town's still-under-construction [[Milton Keynes Central railway station|Central railway station]].<ref name=noadesradio/> Intending to merge Wimbledon with a local Milton Keynes club in order to take up the site, Noades bought [[non-League football|non-League]] club [[Milton Keynes City F.C.|Milton Keynes City]] for <U+00A3>1,{{ref label|MKCity|A|b}}<ref name=mihirbose/> capitalising on the smaller club's financial problems.<ref name=noadesradio/> After Noades and three other Wimbledon directors <U+2013> Jimmy Rose, Bernie Coleman and [[Sam Hammam]] <U+2013> were voted onto MK City's board "in an advisory capacity", Noades emphasised that it was a move by the four directors "for long term investment" and not Wimbledon itself; however, he also claimed that whereas there was "no future for us [Wimbledon] at Plough Lane", "Milton Keynes ha[d] long term potential" and was able to "support a multi-purpose stadium".<ref name=crabtree/> No move (for Wimbledon) occurred and MK City was sold on; Noades later claimed that he had "really [been unable to] see any future in it" and that there was no "means of drawing large attendances to Milton Keynes".<ref name="noadesradio">{{cite news
  | last = Noades
  | first = Ron
  | authorlink = Ron Noades
  | title = I looked at MK in the 70's
  | publisher = [[BBC]]
  | date = 2001-04-01
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/olmedia/1100000/audio/_1101075_noades_dons.ram
  | quote = I certainly looked for alternatives for rehousing Wimbledon, I mean, I could see the limitations in Plough Lane; but the big problem with Wimbledon was, in my view, was that Richmond Park was several square miles of parkland, where there weren't any houses, and it affected Wimbledon's gates compared to other clubs. Yes, we took an interest in Milton Keynes <U+2026> we took a controlling interest in Milton Keynes, at the time they had financial problems, and I went up there, I was in the local press, I met the local authority, and they had a stadium site, right next to the big bus terminal there and the station, the main line route from Euston up to Manchester, and they were very keen to get a Football League club, effectively a franchise if you like, into Milton Keynes to take up that site. <U+2026> I couldn't really see us getting any bigger gates than what Northampton Town were currently getting at that time, and, in fact, are still getting. I really couldn't see any future in it. I can't actually see that there is a means of drawing large attendances to Milton Keynes.
  | accessdate = 2009-05-30 }}</ref><ref name="crabtree">{{cite book 
  | last= Crabtree
  | year=1996
  | page=102<U+2013>105
  | quote=Off the field too, changes were threatened. Chairman Ron Noades claimed that the Borough did not want the club and that he was involved in talks to take Wimbledon to Milton Keynes! ... Once again events off the pitch dominated the thoughts of those who followed the Club. Chairman Ron Noades and three other directors - Jimmy Rose, Bernie Coleman and Sam Hammam - were voted onto the board of Milton Keynes City FC. The chairman stressed: "This is a move by four directors of Wimbledon and not Wimbledon itself. We're there in an advisory capacity and for long term investment". But he warned; "Unless the pre-emption is sorted out there is no future for us at Plough Lane. Milton Keynes has long term potential. It can support a multi-purpose stadium, the potential is there.}}</ref> Noades, who had paid <U+00A3>2,782 for then non-League Wimbledon in 1976,<ref name=noadesindependent/> charged Hammam a figure between <U+00A3>40,000 and <U+00A3>100,000 for the club in 1981 before becoming chairman of nearby [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] during the same year.<ref name=mihirbose/><ref name="noadesindependent">{{cite news
| title = Spirit of the Beehive offers shining example to football's many drones
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/david-conn-spirit-of-the-beehive-offers-shining-example-to-footballs-many-drones-484780.html
| work = [[The Independent]]
| publisher = Independent News & Media
| first = David
| last = Conn
| date = 2005-02-26
| accessdate = 2009-10-31
| location=London}}</ref>

====Luton Town====

[[File:Kenilworth Road.jpg|thumb|right|[[Kenilworth Road]]'s Oak Road End, pictured in 2007]]
[[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]], based in Milton Keynes's neighbouring town of [[Luton]], were also seeking a new site at this time. As early as 1960, then-[[Football League First Division|First Division]] Luton's attendances were deemed "far too low to support a top-flight team" by ''[[Charles Buchan]]<U+2019>s Football Monthly'', which also considered their ground at [[Kenilworth Road]] to be hard to get to.<ref name=wscrelocation1/> Luton already planned to build "a new 50,000-capacity stadium situated to the north-west of the town, near [[Dunstable]]",<ref name=wscrelocation1/> but no new ground materialised, and when Luton were promoted back to the top league at the end of the [[1981<U+2013>82 Football League|1981<U+2013>82]] season, the club was still based at Kenilworth Road. The prospect of moving to Milton Keynes "tempted" Luton's owners; "the local paper dreamed of "MK Hatters" playing in a "super-stadium"".<ref name=wscrelocation1/> The distance from Milton Keynes to Luton is far shorter than that to Wimbledon &ndash; {{convert|20|mi|km|0}} compared to {{convert|56|mi|km|0}} &ndash; but "vehement" resistance from Luton fans prevented the club from moving at this time.<ref name=wscrelocation1/><ref name="wsc1">{{cite web 
| title = Luton Town 1 MK Dons 0  
| publisher = ''[[When Saturday Comes]]'' 
| date = June 2005 
| url = http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/1623/29/ 
| accessdate = 2010-11-22
| quote =Thus the spectre of Luton moving to Milton Keynes has been raised regularly over the years, but the opposition of either the fans (vehement) or the Football League (ironic, given that it was on the basis of a club moving out of its area) always came to the rescue. }}</ref>

[[File:Selhurst Park.jpg|thumb|left|[[Selhurst Park]], Wimbledon's home ground from 1991, pictured in 2010]]
===Wimbledon leave Plough Lane===

After reaching the First Division for the [[1986<U+2013>87 Football League|1986<U+2013>87]] season,<ref name="fchd">{{cite web
|url=http://fchd.info/WIMBLEDO.HTM
|title=Football Club History Database - Wimbledon
|first=Richard
|last=Rundle
|publisher=Football Club History Database
|accessdate=2009-06-06}}</ref> Wimbledon's success as a club in the top-flight of English football was founded on unorthodox financial management and judicious dealings in the transfer market.<ref name="Pitchbattle">{{cite news
| title = Pitch battle
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2003/jan/11/clubsincrisis.sport
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| first = Jim
| last = White
| location = London
| date = 2003-01-11
| accessdate = 2009-06-05
| location=London}}</ref> The team was granted planning permission to build a 20,000-capacity all-seater ground in its home borough of [[London Borough of Merton|Merton]] in 1988,<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> but the site was instead made into a car park by a newly-elected [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] council in 1990.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> Wimbledon's desire to move was made a necessity a year later, when the [[Taylor Report]], which ordered the extensive redevelopment of football grounds, was released.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> When Hammam had purchased the club from Ron Noades, Wimbledon had also owned its ground at Plough Lane,<ref name=mihirbose/> though a pre-emption clause had existed specifying that the ground was only to be used for "sports, leisure or recreational purposes"<ref name=mihirbose/> <U+2013> if Wimbledon Football Club were ever to cease to exist, then Merton Council would be able to buy Plough Lane back for <U+00A3>8,000.<ref name=mihirbose/> This clause reduced the possibility of the club losing its home stadium, but it was unpopular with a succession of Wimbledon owners: Noades stated that there was "no future for [Wimbledon] at Plough Lane" unless the clause were "sorted out",<ref name=crabtree/> and Hammam argued that it incurred upon his ability to borrow money needed to redevelop the ground.<ref name=mihirbose/> Seeking to increase the value of Plough Lane, Hammam entered into negotiations with the council for its removal in 1990; the eventual agreed price for the revoking of the clause was a sum between <U+00A3>300,000 and <U+00A3>800,000.<ref name=mihirbose/> The deal had not been unanimously popular among the owners of Wimbledon <U+2013> at least one club director had resigned his position in protest.<ref name=mihirbose/> Despite the decision to remove the clause, the club could not afford to redevelop Plough Lane when required to do so the following year.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/>

[[File:Wimbledon stadium.jpg|thumb|right|Wimbledon were offered the opportunity to redevelop [[Wimbledon Stadium]], pictured here in 1995, in 1992.]]
As a result, Wimbledon moved across south London before the start of the [[1991<U+2013>92 Football League|1991<U+2013>92]] season to share the [[Selhurst Park]] ground belonging to Noades's Crystal Palace.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> This decision was unpopular among Wimbledon fans, and the club's "already modest" support resultantly took a hit the club could ill-afford.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> Concurrently with this move, the council's recommended proposal of a relocation to a ground in nearby [[Beddington]] fell through.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> With the inflation in costs brought on by the foundation of the [[Premier League|FA Premier League]] in 1992, the club soon began to lose money heavily;<ref name=Pitchbattle /> Hammam attempted to find a new home for the club, and citing what he claimed was "a lack of support" from the local council, sought to relocate within south London to "seven boroughs around us [Wimbledon]",<ref name=thewimbledonwehave/> including [[Tolworth]] and [[Brixton]] <U+2013> insisting, meanwhile, that in the event of such a move the club would be "totally renamed in protest at the lack of council support".<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> Hammam claimed in 2000 to have "looked at every possible site in our borough",<ref name=thewimbledonwehave/> but according to the [[BBC]], he turned down the opportunity to redevelop [[Wimbledon Stadium]] in 1992.<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/> Two years after this, Merton Council, attempting to retain the Plough Lane site for public use, refused to sanction Hammam's proposed sale of the ground for a supermarket redevelopment. Hammam reacted with a "vow never to return to the ground".<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/>

===Hammam gradually withdraws===

While remaining at the club in an advisory role, Hammam sold the club to two Norwegian businessmen, [[Kjell Inge R<U+00F8>kke]] and [[Bj<U+00F8>rn Rune Gjelsten]], in 1997,<ref name="hammamsellsup">{{cite news
| title = Hammam sells up without moving out
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/hammam-sells-up-without-moving-out-1255570.html
| work = [[The Independent]]
| publisher = Independent News & Media
| date = 1997-06-12
| accessdate = 2009-08-31
| location=London
| first=Phil
| last=Shaw}}</ref> and, with political control of Merton Council having changed, he secured the <U+00A3>8 million sale of the Plough Lane site to [[Safeway (UK)|Safeway]] supermarkets in 1998.<ref name=mihirbose/> Hammam unsuccessfully attempted to gain permission to redevelop a former gas works in Merton during the same year,<ref name=mihirbose/> and soon after once again launched abortive negotiations over a site in Beddington.<ref name="mihirbose">{{cite news
| title = Hammam cast in villain's role as Dons seek happy ending
| url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/championship/3010879/Inside-Sport-Hammam-cast-in-villains-role-as-Dons-seek-happy-ending.html
| work = [[The Daily Telegraph]]
| publisher = Telegraph Media Group
| first = Mihir
| last = Bose
| authorlink = Mihir Bose
| date = 2001-08-16
| accessdate = 2009-10-31
| location=London}}</ref> Following this, Hammam started to look further and further afield,<ref name=Pitchbattle /> and despite the anger from a majority of supporters,<ref name=Pitchbattle /> considered [[Basingstoke]], <!-- leave quotation marks, Gatwick is not a town but the BBC reference specifically says "Gatwick".-->"[[Gatwick]]"<!-- leave quotation marks, Gatwick is not a town but the BBC reference specifically says "Gatwick".--> (near [[Crawley]]), [[Dublin]], [[Belfast]], [[Cardiff]] and (non-specifically) "Scotland" as potential new locations for the club,<ref name=toobigfortheirroots/><ref name=thewimbledonwehave/><ref name=womblesontheirway/><ref name=weighupmkmove/> even receiving Premier League approval for Dublin <U+2013> described by Hammam as "an excellent way out of our problems and into cloud nine"<ref name=thewimbledonwehave/> <U+2013> before the idea was vetoed by the [[Football Association of Ireland]].<ref name=mihirbose/> During this time, Wimbledon were also approached by seven other clubs, all from outside of London, each offering to share their home ground.{{ref label|sevenclubs|D|}}<ref name="thewimbledonwehave">{{cite book
  | last = Hammam 
  | year = 2000
  | page = 3
  | quote = In my frustration and facing the realities of Wimbledon having looked at every possible site in our borough, we then actively explored seven boroughs around us, seriously discussed ground sharing with seven clubs, we then widened the horizon and at various times were invited for discussions with Watford, Luton, Birmingham, West Bromwich Albion, Portsmouth, Brighton, Milton Keynes even Hull [sic], these did not pursue seriously though did discuss. However we did discuss and actively look at Scotland and Cardiff. Finally Dublin came into perspective and subject to convincing the fans and addressing a number of practical realities, we considered this to be a serious proposition and an excellent way out of our problems and into cloud nine. }}</ref> After the FAI veto of the move to Dublin, Hammam offered to buy Selhurst Park from Noades, still the owner of the ground despite his sale of Crystal Palace in 1998;<ref name=noadesindependent/> Hammam offered <U+00A3>12 million in 1999, but this plan came to nothing.<ref name=mihirbose/> Hammam subsequently sold his shares in Wimbledon in February 2000,<ref name="hammamleaves1">{{cite news
| title = Hammam sells up at Wimbledon
| url = http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2000/0226/00022600146.html
| work = [[The Irish Times]]
| publisher = The Irish Times Ltd.
| date = 2000-02-26
| location = Dublin
| accessdate = 2009-11-01}}</ref> and became the owner of [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in September of that year.<ref name="hammamleaves2">{{cite news
| title = Hammam's guard revealed to be convicted hooligan
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/hammams-guard-revealed-to-be-convicted-hooligan-662831.html
| work = [[The Independent]]
| publisher = Independent News & Media
| first = Jason
| last = Bennetto
| date = 2002-01-11
| accessdate = 2009-11-01
| location=London}}</ref>

==Milton Keynes proposed again==

[[File:Asda wb.jpg|thumb|left|The development proposed by the Milton Keynes Stadium Consortium included an [[Asda]] superstore and other developments in addition to a football ground.]]
The club was approached by the Milton Keynes Stadium Consortium, led by [[Pete Winkelman]] and supported by [[Asda]] (a subsidiary of [[Wal-Mart]]) and [[IKEA]],<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> in late 2000.<ref name=mihirbose/> This consortium proposed a large development in Milton Keynes, including a 30,000-capacity football stadium,<ref name=wscrelocation2/><ref name=wscrelocation3/> an Asda hypermarket,<ref name=wscrelocation2/> an IKEA store, a hotel,<ref name=wscrelocation3/> a conference centre and a [[retail park]].<ref name=mihirbose/><ref name="wscrelocation2">{{cite web
| title = Don roaming
| publisher = ''[[When Saturday Comes]]''
| date = August 2003
| first = Ian
| last = Pollock
| url = http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/2455/29/
| accessdate = 2009-11-01 }}</ref><ref name="wscrelocation3">{{cite web
| title = Self development
| publisher = ''[[When Saturday Comes]]''
| date = July 2002
| first = Ian
| last = Pollock
| url = http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/2850/29/
| accessdate = 2009-11-01 }}</ref>  The decision to build such a ground was complicated by the fact that the highest ranked team in the town, [[Milton Keynes City F.C.|Milton Keynes City]],{{ref label|MKCity|A|c}}<ref name="mkc">{{cite web
|url=http://www.fchd.info/MILTONKC.HTM
|title=Football Club History Database - Milton Keynes City
|first=Richard
|last=Rundle
|publisher=Football Club History Database
|accessdate=2009-11-01}}</ref> was playing in the then [[English football league system|eighth-tier]] [[Spartan South Midlands Football League|Spartan South Midlands League]], four divisions below The Football League.<ref name=mkc/> The developers could not justify building a stadium of such a size for a club of this small stature,<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> though the system of [[promotion and relegation]] used in English football means that consistent good performance can result in a side rising through the leagues over time <U+2013> indeed, as Wimbledon did themselves during the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=fchd/> However, the Milton Keynes Stadium Consortium resolved instead to "import" an established Football League club to use the ground.<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> Wimbledon fans opposed to the move claimed that the stadium was a "[[Trojan Horse]]" only included in the blueprint to bypass planning rules,<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> and that although the consortium described the Asda superstore as an "enabling development to finance the building of the stadium", the opposite was in fact the case;<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> they claimed that this was why it was so necessary for the consortium to import a team: without a professional club, the ground would not be built, and without the ground, the development could not go ahead.<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> The local Milton Keynes authorities favoured the plan: council leader Norman Miles stated that "[the town] would welcome a major football club", but also implied that the identity of any relocated club was irrelevant, saying that "[i]t could be [[Southend United F.C.|Southend]] or [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] I suppose".<ref name="wscrelocation4">{{cite web
| title = Merton, not Milton
| publisher = ''[[When Saturday Comes]]''
| date = March 2001
| first = Kris
| last = Stewart
| url = http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/3363/29/
| accessdate = 2009-11-01 }}</ref> The consortium had already attempted to relocate [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] to Milton Keynes earlier that year,<ref name=wscrelocation1/><ref name="martinsamuel2july2003">{{cite news
| title = Palios has duty not to bury head in the sand
| url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/columnists/article1147321.ece
| work = [[The Times]]
| publisher = Times Newspapers
| first = Martin
| last = Samuel
| authorlink = Martin Samuel
| date = 2003-07-02
| accessdate = 2009-11-01
| location=London}}</ref> but had been blocked by a [[The Football League|Football League]] decree that "all clubs must stay in their own area".<ref name=wscrelocation1/> After this, the consortium tried to negotiate moves with north London club [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] and Wimbledon's landlords Crystal Palace respectively, but failed to persuade either to take up the proposal.<ref name="wscrelocation1">{{cite web
| title = Relocation, relocation
| publisher = ''[[When Saturday Comes]]''
| date = February 2007
| first = Gavin
| last = Willacy
| url = http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/591/29/
| accessdate = 2009-11-01 
| quote =In the February 1960 edition of Charles Buchan<U+2019>s Football Monthly there was an article entitled <U+201C>The Town that should be ashamed<U+201D>. ... The gist: ... crowds are far too low to support a top-flight team. It reported that most fans come from outlying districts, not Luton itself, transport links are poor and there<U+2019>s nowhere to park. So plans were in place for a new 50,000-capacity stadium situated to the north-west of the town, near Dunstable. Similar discussions have been going on ever since. In 1982 the club were tempted by a move to Milton Keynes: the local paper dreamed of <U+201C>MK Hatters<U+201D> playing in a <U+201C>super-stadium<U+201D>.}}</ref><ref name="weighupmkmove">{{cite news
| title = Dons weigh up Milton Keynes move
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/1100618.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2001-01-04
| quote = Frustration at the difficulty of finding a site in London has led to the club considering moves as far afield as Basingstoke, Gatwick, Cardiff and even Dublin. ... Mr Winkelman revealed he had opened talks with several other clubs including Luton Town, Barnet and Crystal Palace but that Wimbledon were his most favoured candidates.
| accessdate = 2010-12-06}}</ref>

{{location map start |United Kingdom |float=right |width=300}}
{{location map marker |United Kingdom |lat=52.037739  |long=-0.775014 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;position:relative;right:-4px;top:-6px;">[[National&nbsp;Hockey&nbsp;Stadium]]</div>|position=left}}
{{location map marker |United Kingdom |lat=51.398289 |long=-0.085536 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;position:relative;right:-4px;top:-6px;">[[Selhurst Park]]</div>|position=left}}
{{location map marker |United Kingdom |lat=55.838256  |long=-4.228867 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;position:relative;right:0px;">[[Shawfield Stadium|Clyde (old)]]</div>|position=left}}
{{location map marker |United Kingdom |lat=55.944775 |long=-4.037086 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;right:-2px;top:-4px;">[[Broadwood Stadium|Clyde (new)]]</div>|position=left}}
{{location map marker |United Kingdom |lat=55.886167 |long=-3.522872 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;right:18px;relative;top:12px;">[[Almondvale Stadium|Livingston]]</div>|position=right}}
{{location map marker |United Kingdom |lat=55.95704 |long=-3.158781 |label=<div style="font-size:80%;position:relative;right:22px;top:-6px;">[[Meadowbank Stadium|Meadowbank&nbsp;Thistle]]</div>|position=right}}
{{location map end |United Kingdom |caption=Although club relocations had taken place in Scotland during the 1990s, they were not over such great distances.}}

The consortium's offer was initially turned down by Wimbledon,<ref name=mihirbose/> but Charles Koppel, the new chairman appointed by the Norwegian owners in January 2001,<ref name="koppelchairman">{{cite news
| title = Move or die: 'A whole raft of us believe it is better to live, even if somewhere else'
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/move-or-die-a-whole-raft-of-us-believe-it-is-better-to-live-even-if-somewhere-else-603858.html
| work = [[The Independent]]
| publisher = Independent News & Media
| date = 2002-11-10
| accessdate = 2009-08-31
| location=London}}</ref> was in favour of the move.<ref name=mihirbose/> Koppel claimed that the club's owners were subsidising it to the tune of "around <U+00A3>6 million a year" and that "if the club d[id] not move [it] w[ould] die".<ref name=mihirbose/> The Milton Keynes consortium, meanwhile, had turned its attention to west London club [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]. Just as the consortium had always maintained that the Wimbledon name, colours and badge would remain even after any potential relocation,<ref name=nonamechangehonest/> QPR were promised that the club name and blue-and-white hooped strip would be kept if the team moved.<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> QPR were also offered "supporter representation on the [club's] board".<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> Despite being in financial [[administration (law)|administration]], QPR turned down the offer made by the consortium at the end of the [[2000<U+2013>01 Football League|2000<U+2013>01]] season,<ref name=mihirbose/> leading the consortium to once again contact Wimbledon in June 2001 with a "firmed up" proposal.<ref name=mihirbose/> With Koppel now in charge, the club was more receptive to the idea.<ref name=mihirbose/> As talks progressed, Winkelman began to register various internet [[domain name]]s relating to "MK Dons",<ref name=wisaindependentreview/> and approached the owner of Milton Keynes City, attempting to buy the club name.<ref name="wisaindependentreview">{{cite news
| title = Submission by the Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association to the Independent European Football Review
| url = http://www.independentfootballreview.com/doc/comments/33.pdf
| publisher = Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association
| date = 2006-03-12
| accessdate = 2009-11-01}}</ref> Although fans were "angrily opposed to the plans",<ref name=itsmiltonkeynes2001/> Koppel announced in August 2001 that the club intended to relocate to the new town;<ref name="itsmiltonkeynes2001">{{cite news
| title = League warns Dons over move
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/1483683.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2001-08-10
| accessdate = 2009-08-31}}</ref> the club made a formal application for the
Football League<U+2019>s approval at the same time.<ref name="reportofindependentcommision">{{cite news
| title = Report of the Independent Commission on Wimbledon F.C.'s wish to relocate to Milton Keynes
| url = http://www.wisa.org.uk/cgi/l/files/20020530_fa.pdf
| publisher = [[The Football Association]]
| accessdate = 2009-06-05}}</ref> Meanwhile, the local council claimed that Noades had agreed to sell the Selhurst Park ground to Wimbledon <U+2013> something which Noades denied.<ref name=mihirbose/>

The proposed move to Milton Keynes was opposed in most quarters: a majority of Wimbledon fans "fiercely opposed" it, as well as both [[The Football Association]] and The Football League.<ref name=Pitchbattle /><ref name=reportofindependentcommision/><ref name=movegetsgoahead/> Although relocation of a Football League club across such a distance was unprecedented, similar moves had occurred within the [[Scottish Football League]] during the 1990s: [[Glasgow]] club [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]] and [[Edinburgh]]-based [[Livingston F.C.|Meadowbank Thistle]] had migrated to the new towns of [[Cumbernauld]] and [[Livingston, Scotland|Livingston]] respectively, with Meadowbank actually adopting the name of the town on moving (they dropped the suffix "Thistle").<ref name="clyde">{{cite web
| title = A Fresh Start - Broadwood - 1994-Present
| url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/club/history/fresh-start/
| publisher = [[Clyde F.C.]]
| accessdate = 2010-11-23}}</ref><ref name="livi">{{cite web
| title = Meadowbank Thistle FC - a history
| url = http://www.livingstonfc.co.uk/history/history_meadowbank.php
| publisher = [[Livingston F.C.]]
| accessdate = 2010-11-23}}</ref> The Football League told the consortium that any Milton Keynes club would have to earn membership by "progress[ing] through the [[English football league system|pyramid]]" and unanimously rejected Wimbledon's application to move.<ref name=wscrelocation4/><ref name=reportofindependentcommision/> However, when the decision was contested by the club, an arbitration panel was formed, made up of Association vice-chairman [[David Dein]] (also vice-chairman of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]), [[York City F.C.|York City]] chairman [[Douglas Craig]] and Charles Hollander [[Queen's Counsel|QC]].<ref name=reportofindependentcommision/><ref name="appealformove">{{cite news
| title = FA backs Wimbledon appeal
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/1741876.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2002-01-29
| accessdate = 2009-08-31}}</ref><ref name="afcwinconfsouth">{{cite news
| title = Tears of joy as AFC Wimbledon prove they are in the wider interest of football
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/blog/2009/apr/28/afc-wimbledon-blue-square-conference-south-champions
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| first = David
| last = Conn
| date = 2009-04-28
| accessdate = 2009-06-05
| location=London}}</ref> Before the arbitration panel heard Wimbledon's appeal in January 2002, Winkelman claimed that even if the move was turned down, "[the] door w[ould] be open to any club in trouble [to attempt to relocate to Milton Keynes]";<ref name="doorwillbeopen">{{cite news
| title = Mr Milton Keynes: 'Our door will be open to any club in trouble'
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/mr-milton-keynes-our-door-will-be-open-to-any-club-in-trouble-663980.html
| work = [[The Independent]]
| publisher = Independent News & Media
| first = Alan
| last = Hubbard
| date = 2002-01-20
| accessdate = 2009-10-31
| location=London}}</ref> however, the panel unanimously decided that the decision taken had "not been properly taken in the legal sense, and that the procedures had not been fair",<ref name=reportofindependentcommision/> meaning that the possibility of Wimbledon relocating remained open.<ref name=reportofindependentcommision/> As a result of this verdict, the League board reconvened on 17 April 2002 to reconsider the proposal, and concluded that the matter should be considered by an independent commission appointed by The Football Association.<ref name=reportofindependentcommision/> The commission members chosen by the FA were solicitor Raj Parker, FA Council member Alan Turvey (also Chairman of the [[Isthmian League]]) and [[Steve Stride]], the Operations Director at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref name=reportofindependentcommision/> The commission ruled in favour of the move, by two votes to one, on 28 May 2002.<ref name="movegetsgoahead">{{cite news
| title = Dons get Milton Keynes green light
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/2012312.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2002-05-28
| accessdate = 2009-08-31}}</ref><ref name=reportofindependentcommision/>

==Foundation of AFC Wimbledon and relocation of Wimbledon F.C.==
{{double image|left|National hockey stadium.jpg|120|AFCWvsRamsgate.jpg|160|Wimbledon F.C.'s final home matches were played at the [[National Hockey Stadium]] in [[Milton Keynes]] (left, pictured in 2008). [[AFC Wimbledon]], meanwhile, began to share [[Kingstonian F.C.|Kingstonian]]'s ground at [[Kingsmeadow]] (right, pictured in 2007) in [[London Borough of Merton|Merton]]'s neighbouring borough of [[Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames|Kingston upon Thames]].}}
:''From this point Wimbledon F.C. is named in full in order to disambiguate from AFC Wimbledon.''
The FA made it clear that although the decision was final and binding, it strongly opposed the relocation.<ref name=movegetsgoahead/> The Association's Chief Executive, [[Adam Crozier]], publicly stated that it was an "appalling decision",<ref name="crozier">{{cite news
| title = Crozier 'appalled' by Dons move
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/2209767.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2002-08-22
| accessdate = 2009-06-05}}</ref> while the Association itself revealed that it had submitted to the commission its opposition to the move.<ref name=movegetsgoahead/> Many Wimbledon F.C. fans were "left devastated by the decision",<ref name=movegetsgoahead/> and, calling it the "death of [their] club",<ref name=movegetsgoahead/> founded their own team, [[AFC Wimbledon]], weeks after the move's approval.<ref name=Pitchbattle /> The new club entered a [[groundshare|groundsharing]] arrangement with [[Kingstonian F.C.|Kingstonian]], moving into the latter club's home ground of [[Kingsmeadow]] in the [[Royal Borough of Kingston upon Thames]], adjacent to the original side's home borough of [[London Borough of Merton|Merton]].<ref name=womblesontheirway/> Meanwhile, Wimbledon F.C. became pejoratively nicknamed by some as "Franchise F.C." (FFC).<ref name="womblesontheirway">{{cite news
| first = Ivor
| last = Heller
| title = Wombles are on their way
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2002/sep/01/sport.comment7
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2002-09-01
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref> AFC Wimbledon claimed that since forming, their average attendance was 3,700 and that the gates of Wimbledon F.C. had been affected as a result.<ref name=womblesontheirway/>  This situation meant that during the [[2002<U+2013>03 in English football|2002&ndash;03]] season, Wimbledon F.C.'s last full term at Selhurst Park, attendances at Wimbledon F.C. matches fell below those at Kingsmeadow possibly due to the fact that a number of local fans were now following AFC Wimbledon instead.<ref name=womblesontheirway/><ref name="lowesteverdiv1crowd">{{cite news
| first = Alistair
| last = Moffitt
| title = Dons chief shrugs off lowest ever crowd
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2002/oct/31/newsstory.sport3
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2002-10-31
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref> Wimbledon F.C.'s resultant lower income contributed to the club entering administration in June 2003.<ref name="donsflowinfront">{{cite news
| first = Robert
| last = Pryce
| title = The Dons flow in front of the few
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2002/aug/26/match.sport1
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2002-08-26
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref><ref name="administration">{{cite news
| title = Wimbledon go into administration
| url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2405494/Wimbledon-go-into-administration.html
| work = [[The Daily Telegraph]]
| publisher = Telegraph Media Group
| date = 2003-06-06
| accessdate = 2009-06-05
| location=London}}</ref> A month later, the largest football team in Milton Keynes, Milton Keynes City, went out of business due to a lack of investment.<ref name="goinggoing">{{cite news
  | title = City left fighting for their survival
  | work = Milton Keynes Today
  | publisher = Johnston Press Digital Publishing
  | date = 2003-06-05
  | url = http://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/sport/City-left-fighting-for-their.528192.jp
  | location = Milton Keynes
  | accessdate = 2009-06-04 }}</ref><ref name="gone">{{cite news
  | title = City club on the brink of folding
  | work = Milton Keynes Today
  | publisher = Johnston Press Digital Publishing
  | date = 2003-07-03
  | location = Milton Keynes
  | url = http://www.miltonkeynestoday.co.uk/ViewArticle2.aspx?SectionID=416&ArticleID=554102
  | accessdate = 2009-06-04 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

Weeks before Wimbledon F.C.'s entry into administration, [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] had been purchased by a consortium of "businessmen" from Hong Kong and the United States.<ref name="gurneylondonluton"></ref>  The "public face" of the consortium was John Gurney, a man who in 1999 had been arrested and remanded on a charge of "conspiracy to import cocaine", charges he was subsequently cleared of.<ref name="gurneylondonluton"></ref>  Gurney had floated the idea of buying Wimbledon F.C. and merging the club with Luton Town "effectively buying a back door to Division One".{{ref label|ltfc2003|E|}} Gurney said that he would approach the Wimbledon F.C. administrators to find out the terms as "it does no harm to ask the question".<ref name="gurneylondonluton"></ref>  Further ideas from Gurney included the building of a "70,000-capacity stadium" near Junction 10 on the [[M1 Motorway|M1]] and the possible renaming of the club to London Luton after [[London Luton Airport|the airport]]".<ref name="gurneylondonluton">{{cite news
| first = Michael
| last = Walker
| title = Luton directors quit as far-fetched merger is mooted
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2003/jun/10/newsstory.sport8
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2003-06-10
| accessdate = 2010-12-06
| location=London
| quote=Two directors of Luton Town, including the fans' representative on the board, resigned yesterday in protest at the uncertainty surrounding the club. Their decision came on the day the man who may or may not be the new owner of the club raised the far-fetched possibility of Luton merging with Wimbledon. John Gurney, who while at Farnborough Town in 1999 was arrested and remanded in Winchester prison on a charge of conspiracy to import cocaine, arrived at Kenilworth Road three weeks ago. Cleared of the charge, he is the public face of an otherwise mysterious consortium of "businessmen" from as far afield as Hong Kong and the United States. ... "Should we buy them, merge them with Luton and play at Luton, effectively buying a back door to Division One?" Gurney asked of Wimbledon on Luton's website. "We will approach the administrator [of Wimbledon] to find out the terms, because it does no harm to ask the question." Unfortunately for Gurney, asking the question will do harm to his already limited credibility in English football in general and Luton in particular. The Football League, anxious not to inflame the situation, insisted diplomatically that it would "consider any move on its merits", but realistically there is no chance of a Luton-Wimbledon merger application being successful. ... With four directors already gone, the first resignation yesterday was that of Yvonne Fletcher, the fans' representative, who works for this newspaper. ... Luton, who finished ninth in the Second Division, lose some <U+00A3>3m-<U+00A3>4m a year and have unpaid bills in the region of <U+00A3>500,000. But Watson-Challis recently acquired a substantial plot of land near Junction 10 on the M1. It is claimed that the land has a commercial development value of <U+00A3>50m. Gurney has spoken of building a 70,000-capacity stadium there. Merging with Wimbledon is not his first fantastical suggestion, and he has also wondered aloud about changing the club's name to London Luton after the airport. ... She summed up the past three weeks at Kenilworth Road as "a complete nightmare, kind of Kafkaesque".}}</ref> Neither idea however was followed up. After six weeks of Gurney ownership described by supporters' representative Yvonne Fletcher as "a complete nightmare, kind of [[Franz Kafka|Kafkaesque]]",<ref name=gurneylondonluton/> Luton entered administrative receivership themselves "as a protective measure", resulting in Gurney's departure and the abandoning of his plans.<ref name="gurney3">{{cite news
| first = John
| last = Gurney
| title = A report on Luton Town Football Club
| url = http://www.lutontown.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10372~389395,00.html
| publisher = Luton Town F.C.
| date = 2003-06-10
| accessdate = 2010-12-07
| location=Luton}}</ref><ref name="gurney2">{{cite news
| title = Hatters call in the receivers
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2003/jul/14/newsstory.sport11
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2003-07-14
| accessdate = 2010-12-06
| location=London}}</ref>

After starting the [[2003<U+2013>04 in English football|2003&ndash;04]] season at Selhurst Park, the first Wimbledon F.C. match in Milton Keynes was played on 27 September 2003 &ndash; a 2&ndash;2 draw with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at the [[National Hockey Stadium]], temporarily converted for football use pending construction of the new stadium.<ref name="firstmatchatmk">{{cite news
| first = Robert
| last = Pryce
| title = Wimbledon's happy ending is pure Hollywood
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2003/sep/29/match.burnley
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2003-09-29
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref><ref name="relegated2004">{{cite news
| first = Adrian
| last = Milledge
| title = Wimbledon fall through trap-door
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2004/apr/07/match.sunderland
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2004-04-07
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref> The club struggled both on and off the pitch throughout the season, spending its entirety in administration and eventually finishing bottom of the second-tier First Division.<ref name=fchd/><ref name=relegated2004/><ref name="finalwhistleforwimbledon">{{cite news
| first = Stuart
| last = Watson
| title = The final whistle for Wimbledon?
| url = http://www.propertyweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=39&storycode=3035621
| work = [[Property Week]]
| publisher = [[United Business Media]]
| location = London
| date = 2004-05-14
| accessdate = 2009-06-04}}</ref> An article appeared in British journal ''[[Property Week]]'' in May 2004, after Wimbledon F.C. had been relegated,<ref name=fchd/><ref name=relegated2004/> stating that the construction of the new stadium would be cancelled were Wimbledon F.C. to go out of business;<ref name=finalwhistleforwimbledon/> in response, Richard Foreman, a director of the consortium's development consultant, stated that "the scheme w[ould] go ahead"<ref name=finalwhistleforwimbledon/> with "the total support of the council"<ref name=finalwhistleforwimbledon/> were this to happen.<ref name=finalwhistleforwimbledon/> On the subject of who would occupy the new stadium, Foreman added that the consortium would "have a year and a half to find another club [to relocate to Milton Keynes]".<ref name=finalwhistleforwimbledon/>  Winkelman's consortium brought the club out of administration in June 2004,<ref name="outofadmin">{{cite news
| title = Wimbledon to change name
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/3825865.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2004-06-21
| accessdate = 2009-06-05}}</ref> and although it had originally stated that the name "Wimbledon F.C." would remain in place regardless of the move,<ref name="nonamechangehonest">{{cite news
| title = No name change for Wimbledon, despite the move
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2003/apr/02/newsstory.sport
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2003-04-02
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref> changed the club's name, badge and colours soon after.<ref name="becomemkdons">{{cite news
| title = Wimbledon become MK Dons FC
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2004/jun/21/newsstory.mkdons
| work = [[The Guardian]]
| publisher = Guardian News and Media
| date = 2004-06-21
| accessdate = 2009-06-04
| location=London}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
{{Main|Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|AFC Wimbledon}}{{Football kit box |
  align      = right |
  pattern_la=_yellowborder|pattern_b=_thinyellowsides|pattern_ra=_yellowborder|
  pattern_sh  = _yellowsides|
  pattern_so = |
  leftarm    = 0000ff |
  body       = 0000ff |
  rightarm   = 0000ff |
  shorts     = 0000ff |
  socks      = 0000ff |
  title      = [[AFC Wimbledon]]'s original colours
}}{{Football kit box |
  align      = right |
  pattern_la=_blackborder|pattern_b=_blackcollar|pattern_ra=_blackborder|
  pattern_sh  = |
  pattern_so = |
  leftarm    = ffffff |
  body       = ffffff |
  rightarm   = ffffff |
  shorts     = ffffff |
  socks      = ffffff |
  title      = [[Milton Keynes Dons]]' original colours
}}
===Identity===
The new name of the club was "[[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons Football Club]]",<ref name=becomemkdons/> a name made up of the team's new location and a common nickname of Wimbledon-based sports teams, "[[Dons|The Dons]]". Winkelman's consortium claimed that the name was intended to "represent the past, present and future and place the club at the heart of its new community"<ref name=becomemkdons/> as well as to "retain a link with its former identity".<ref name=becomemkdons/> The blue and yellow colours that Wimbledon F.C. players had worn were replaced by an all-white strip,<ref name = "HFKMK">{{cite web| title = Historical Kits Milton Keynes Dons
| url = http://historicalkits.co.uk/Milton_Keynes_Dons/Milton_Keynes_Dons.htm
| first = Dave
| last = Moor
| publisher = Historical Kits
| accessdate = 2009-11-04}}</ref> while the club badge became an rendering of the letters "MK", the "K" positioned below the "M", rotated 90<U+00B0> anti-clockwise and defaced with the year "MMIV" (2004).<ref name = HFKMK/> AFC Wimbledon, meanwhile, founded in 2002 to attempt to continue the original club's identity,<ref name=womblesontheirway/><ref name=donsflowinfront/> adopted a home kit of blue and yellow,<ref name = "afcw">{{cite web| title = AFC Wimbledon
| url = http://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/index.php?Psection_id=1
| publisher = [[AFC Wimbledon]]
| accessdate = 2009-11-04}}</ref> emulating the uniform worn by Wimbledon F.C.<ref name = "HFK">{{cite web| title = Historical Kits Wimbledon
| url = http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Wimbledon/Wimbledon.htm
| first = Dave
| last = Moor
| publisher = Historical Kits
| accessdate = 2009-06-03}}</ref> In a similar vein, the emblem chosen by AFC Wimbledon was, like the Wimbledon F.C. badge, based on the coat of arms of the [[Municipal Borough of Wimbledon]],<ref name = afcw/> and the traditional local nickname, "The Dons", was established as the club's nickname.<ref name = afcw/>

[[File:StadiumMKEnglandU21.jpg|thumb|left|[[Stadium:mk]], pictured in 2009]]
===The new stadium===
{{Main|National Hockey Stadium|Stadium:mk}}
<!--Only include here information relevant to the ground's construction and opening; anything further should be referred to the linked article-->
After first playing at the [[National Hockey Stadium]] in September 2003,<ref name="nationalhockeystadium1">{{cite news
| title = Wimbledon move gets go-ahead
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/3114084.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2003-09-19
| accessdate = 2010-01-03}}</ref> the club continued to use the ground following its June 2004 rebranding. Work on the "[[Stadium:mk|Denbigh Stadium]]" had not yet even begun; despite its original proposed opening time of the [[2004<U+2013>05 in English football|2004<U+2013>05]] season, ground was not broken on the intended 30,000-capacity stadium until February 2005.<ref name="donsstadiumcut">{{cite news
| title = First turf cut for Dons' stadium
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/beds/bucks/herts/4274475.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2005-02-17
| accessdate = 2010-01-03}}</ref> After the club set a new target of January 2007 in December 2005,<ref name="donsstadiumdate">{{cite news
| title = MK Dons fix stadium launch date
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/4501170.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2005-12-05
| first = John
| last = Sinnott
| accessdate = 2010-01-03}}</ref> February 2007 saw a revised proposal of a 22,000-seater ground ready in July of that year, with provision for expansion to 32,000.<ref name="donsstadiumdate2">{{cite news
| title = Milton Keynes stadium is on track
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/6366309.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2007-02-15
| accessdate = 2010-01-03}}</ref> The first match at the ground, by now renamed "Stadium:mk" was played in July 2007.<ref name="donsstadiumdate3">{{cite news
| title = Dons open stadium against Chelsea
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/6906212.stm
| publisher = [[BBC]]
| date = 2007-07-19
| accessdate = 2010-01-03}}</ref>

===History and honours===
[[File:The FA Cup Trophy.jpg|thumb|right|Among the Wimbledon F.C. trophies and memorabilia returned to Merton in 2007 was a replica of the [[FA Cup]] (actual trophy pictured) won by the club in 1988.]]
The location of the history and legacy of Wimbledon F.C., as well as the honours won by the club, remained open to debate for five years after the relocation's confirmation on 28 May 2002.<ref name="lettertofa">{{cite web
|url=http://www.wisa.org.uk/cgi/l/articles/index.cgi?action=show&id=343
|title=Open Letter To The Football Association
|date= 2003-05-28
|accessdate=2009-11-04
|publisher= Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association}}</ref><ref name=fourfourtwowinkelman/> In the view of AFC Wimbledon and its supporters, "[t]he identity of a football club is implicitly bound up in its community",<ref name=lettertofa/><ref name = "afcw2">{{cite web| title = AFC Wimbledon Honours
| url = http://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/honours.php?Psection_id=4&Psub_section_id=7&squad=
| publisher = [[AFC Wimbledon]]
| accessdate = 2009-11-04}}</ref> while on the other hand, Pete Winkelman claimed in November 2004 that "we're the real child of Wimbledon".<ref name=fourfourtwowinkelman/> By now chairman of Milton Keynes Dons, Winkelman said during the same interview that "both the MK Dons and AFC Wimbledon share the same heritage",<ref name=fourfourtwowinkelman/> but also that the founders of AFC Wimbledon had "left their team before their team left them".<ref name="fourfourtwowinkelman">{{cite journal
 | date = 2004-11
 | title = Interview & Comment: Pete Winkelman
 | publisher = Haymarket Group
 | location = London
 | journal = FourFourTwo
 }}</ref> Winkelman went on to say that he would retain the trophies and history of Wimbledon F.C. in Milton Keynes, because AFC Wimbledon had "abdicated their right to it when they all walked away."<ref name=fourfourtwowinkelman/> Despite Winkelman's claims, the history and honours eventually found their way back to Merton in August 2007, a year after extensive negotiations had been completed between the Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association, Milton Keynes Dons F.C., the Milton Keynes Dons Supporters Association and the [[Football Supporters Federation]].<ref name=honourstomerton/> Milton Keynes Dons announced at the same time that they considered themselves to be a new club, formed in 2004, and renounced all claims to a club history before this point.<ref name="honourstomerton">{{cite web
|url=http://www.wisa.org.uk/cgi/l/articles/index.cgi?action=show&id=558
|title=History and Honours of Wimbledon FC returned to Merton
|date= 2007-08-02
|accessdate=2009-11-04
|publisher= Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association}}</ref> As a result of these developments, the WISA revoked its call for supporters to boycott Milton Keynes Dons matches played in Milton Keynes and removed its objection to Milton Keynes Dons fans joining the Football Supporters Federation.<ref name=honourstomerton/> The Wimbledon F.C. trophies and memorabilia were subsequently put on public display at Morden Library in Merton in April 2008.<ref name="mordenlibrary">{{cite web
|url=http://www.merton.gov.uk/my_merton_issue_28_final_proof.pdf
|title=It<U+2019>s come home
|date= 2008-04
|accessdate=2009-11-04
|publisher= Merton Borough Council}}</ref>

===Players and staff===
The Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association, by now affiliated to AFC Wimbledon, formed the Wimbledon Old Players Association (WOPA) in September 2005 "as part of its campaign to reclaim the history of Wimbledon Football Club for AFC Wimbledon and/or the community of Wimbledon".<ref name="WOPA1">{{cite web
|url=http://www.wisa.org.uk/wopa/news1.html
|title=WISA launches the Wimbledon Old Players Association
|date= 2005-09-12
|accessdate=2009-11-04
|publisher= Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association}}</ref> Membership was opened to any former Wimbledon F.C. or AFC Wimbledon player or manager; there were sixty founder members.<ref name=WOPA1/> The AFC Wimbledon-backed WOPA team competed as Wimbledon in the [[Masters Football|London Masters]] tournament in July 2006.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.wisa.org.uk/wopa/news7.html
|title=Wimbledon Masters Are Back
|date= 2006-05-23
|accessdate=2009-11-04
|publisher= Wimbledon Independent Supporters Association}}</ref>

